---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base title="N9 Archive" active="home">
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-[36rem] px-6 pt-20 pb-24 md:pt-28 md:pb-32">
    <p class="mb-8 text-[11px] font-medium uppercase tracking-[0.28em] text-n9-500">
      For the Nokia N9 · MeeGo Harmattan
    </p>

    <h1
      class="font-serif text-5xl font-normal leading-[1.05] tracking-tight text-white md:text-6xl"
      style="font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 60;"
    >
      Still on.
    </h1>

    <div
      class="mt-12 space-y-7 font-serif text-[1.0625rem] leading-[1.7] text-n9-200 md:text-[1.125rem]"
      style="font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 16;"
    >
      <p>
        The Nokia N9 shipped in 2011 with a gesture-driven OS nobody else
        made, and a year later Nokia walked away from it. The hardware kept
        working. So did the people who liked it. This is where their work
        lives.
      </p>

      <p>
        A working device needs <a href="/guides/developer-mode" class="archive-link">developer
        mode</a> turned on first — the one switch that opens the phone up to
        anything beyond the App Store. After that, the
        <a href="/packages" class="archive-link">package catalog</a>
        holds the original Nokia binaries, the Harmattan SDK, the community
        apps and developer tools, and the OpenRepos collection, each with
        install commands and descriptions intact.
      </p>

      <p>
        A bricked device is its own thing. The
        <a href="/guides/flashing" class="archive-link">flashing guide</a>
        walks through reviving one or installing firmware from scratch, with
        <a href="/guides/flasher-troubleshooting" class="archive-link">troubleshooting
        notes</a> for the parts that tend to go wrong;
        <a href="/firmware" class="archive-link">firmware images</a> for every
        region are kept alongside it. If the work goes past flashing, the
        <a href="/manuals" class="archive-link">service manual and schematics</a>
        are here too.
      </p>

      <p>
        The <a href="/docs/" class="archive-link">Harmattan developer
        documentation</a> is here in full, verbatim from the offline Nokia
        site, and the
        <a href="/design" class="archive-link">design archive</a> keeps the
        original Nokia Pure typeface, the CoreUI toolkit, and the launcher
        icon kit Nokia shipped to developers in 2011. The rest of the
        <a href="/guides/" class="archive-link">guides</a> collect the small
        fixes that come up when a phone is fifteen years old.
      </p>

      <p class="text-n9-300">
        Free to use. The
        <a href="https://github.com/mpwsh/n9-portal" rel="noopener" class="archive-link">source
        is on GitHub</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
